Document: audio_buses
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_buses.rst
Summary: Adding effects to audio buses and their limitations on the web platform

Warning: This feature is not supported on the web platform if the AudioStreamPlayer's playback mode is set to Sample (default). It will only work if playback mode is set to Stream, which increases latency if threads are not enabled. See doc_exporting_for_web_audio_playback for details.

Audio buses can contain all sorts of effects. These effects modify the sound in one way or another and are applied in order. For information on what each effect does, see doc_audio_effects.
---CHUNK---
Document: Audio Buses
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_buses.rst
Summary: Godot automatically disables unused audio buses and indicates them with a blue VU meter.

Automatic bus disabling
There is no need to disable buses manually when not in use. Godot detects that the bus has been silent for a few seconds and disables it (including all effects). Disabled buses have a blue VU meter instead of a red-green one.
---CHUNK---
Document: audio_buses
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_buses.rst
Summary: Explains how Stream Players reference audio buses by name and the implications of renaming or rearranging buses.

Stream Players use bus names to identify a bus, which allows adding, removing and moving buses around while the reference to them is kept. However, if a bus is renamed, the reference will be lost and the Stream Player will output to Master. This system was chosen because rearranging buses is a more common process than renaming them.
---CHUNK---
Document: audio_buses
Path: godot/tutorials/audio/audio_buses.rst
Summary: The default bus layout file location and ability to save/load custom bus arrangements.

The default bus layout is automatically saved to the ``res://default_bus_layout.tres`` file. Custom bus arrangements can be saved and loaded from disk.